      <div class=3D"section main sidebar-both">
        <div class=3D"section-container main-container sidebar-both-contain=
er">
          <div class=3D"section main-inner sidebar-both-inner">
            <div class=3D"pad-grid">
              <div class=3D"col-custom content sidebar-both-content">
                <h1 role=3D"main">Rounding Numbers</h1>
                <div class=3D"w3-container hide-print" style=3D"padding:20p=
x 0;">
                  <p style=3D"text-align:center;"><button disabled=3D"" cla=
ss=3D"w3-btn" style=3D"color:#000; background-color:#f1f1f1;">General</butt=
on><a class=3D"w3-btn" href=3D"https://www.purplemath.com/modules/rounding2=
.htm" style=3D"background-color:#f1f1f1;">Sig-Digs</a><a class=3D"w3-btn" h=
ref=3D"https://www.purplemath.com/modules/rounding3.htm" style=3D"backgroun=
d-color:#f1f1f1;">More Sig-Digs</a></p>
                </div>
                <div class=3D"grid">
                  <div class=3D"col-half tablet-col-half">
                    <h2 class=3D"section-title hide-print">Purplemath</h2>
                    <!-- id=3D"lesson" marks beginning of content -->
                    <p class=3D"text" id=3D"lesson">When you have to round =
a number, you are usually told how to round it. It's simplest when you're t=
old how many "places" to round to, but you should also know how to round to=
 a named "place", such as "to the nearest thousand" or "to the ten-thousand=
ths place". You may also need to know how to round to a certain number of s=
ignificant digits; we'll get to that later.</p>
                <p class=3D"text">In general, you round to a given place by=
 looking at the digit one place to the right of the "target" place. If the =
digit is a five or greater, you round the target digit up by one. Otherwise=
, you leave the target as it is. Then you replace any digits to the right w=
ith zeroes (if they are to the left of the decimal point) or else you delet=
e the digits (if they are past the decimal point).</p>
                    <div class=3D"hide-print"><!-- hiding YT text on printe=
d pages -->
                    <p class=3D"display-mobile content-continues" style=3D"=
padding-top:20px;">Content Continues Below</p>
                    </div><!-- /hiding YT text on printed pages -->
                  </div>
                  <!-- col-half tablet-col-half -->
                 =20
                  <div class=3D"col-half tablet-col-half hide-print">
                    <!-- START MathHelp.com Lesson Page Insert -->
                    <div id=3D"mh_callout">
                      <h2 class=3D"section-title-2">MathHelp.com</h2>
                      <div id=3D"mh_lesson_display" align=3D"center">
                        <a href=3D"https://member.mathhelp.com/courses/midd=
le_and_high_school/98/chapter/4/lesson/54?id=3D54&amp;utm_campaign=3Dpurple=
math&amp;utm_source=3Drounding.htm&amp;utm_medium=3Dbanner&amp;tab=3Dinstru=
ction&amp;tabItem=3D1"><img src=3D"https://www.mathhelp.com/images/lesson-d=
etail/screenshots/285x200-play/1054-gui.jpg" alt=3D"Rounding Numbers on Mat=
hHelp.com" width=3D"285" height=3D"200"></a>
                      </div><!-- mh_lesson_display -->
                      <div id=3D"mh_notice">
                        <p style=3D"text-align:center;"><a href=3D"https://=
member.mathhelp.com/courses/middle_and_high_school/98/chapter/4/lesson/54?i=
d=3D54&amp;utm_campaign=3Dpurplemath&amp;utm_source=3Drounding.htm&amp;utm_=
medium=3Dbanner&amp;tab=3Dinstruction&amp;tabItem=3D1" style=3D"text-decora=
tion:none;">Rounding Decimals</a></p>
                      </div><!-- mh_notice -->
                    </div><!-- mh_callout-->
                    <!-- END MathHelp.com Lesson Page Insert -->
                  </div>
                  <!-- col-half tablet-col-half hide-print -->=20
                 =20
                </div>
                <!-- grid -->
               =20
                <p class=3D"text">I'll use the first few digits of the deci=
mal expansion of <span class=3D"math">=CF=80</span>: <span class=3D"math">3=
.14159265...</span> in the examples below.</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <h4 class=3D"text question">Round <span class=3D"math">=
=CF=80</span> to five places.</h4>
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <div class=3D"indent_prob">
                  <p class=3D"text">"To five places" means "to five decimal=
 places". First, I count out the five decimal places, and then I look at th=
e sixth place:</p>
                  <div class=3D"indent_prob">
                    <p class=3D"math">3.14159 | 265...</p>
                  </div>
                  <p class=3D"text">I've drawn a little line separating the=
 fifth place from the sixth place. This can be a handy way of "keeping your=
 place", especially if you are dealing with lots of digits.</p>
                  <div class=3D"alignright display-mobile nomargin hide-pri=
nt" style=3D"width:180px; min-height:215px;"><!-- contracted ad for mobile =
-->
                    <p class=3D"in-lesson-resp-ad-header nomargin" align=3D=
"center">Affiliate</p>
                    <div id=3D"contract_ad" style=3D"text-align:center; mar=
gin:10px 0px 10px 15px;">
                      <ins data-revive-zoneid=3D"2" data-revive-id=3D"22fb1=
2d5af67c91fb385a68f631b6803"></ins>
                     =20
                    </div>
                  </div><!-- /contracted ad for mobile -->
                  <p class=3D"text">The fifth place has a <span class=3D"ma=
th">9</span> in it. Looking at the sixth place, I see that it has a <span c=
lass=3D"math">2</span> in it. Since <span class=3D"math">2</span> is less t=
han five, I won't round the <span class=3D"math">9</span> up; that is, I'll=
 leave the <span class=3D"math">9</span> as it is. In addition, I will dele=
te the digits after the <span class=3D"math">9</span>. Then <span class=3D"=
math">=CF=80</span>, rounded to five places, is:</p>
                  <div class=3D"indent_prob">
                    <p class=3D"math answer">3.14159</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <hr>
                <div class=3D"hide-print hide-mobile">
                <!-- WyzAnt text-link ad for non-mobile -->
                <p class=3D"in-lesson-resp-ad-header">Affiliate</p>
                  <div class=3D"in-lesson-resp-ad"><a href=3D"https://www.w=
yzant.com/algebra_1_tutors.aspx?utm_source=3Dpartners&amp;utm_medium=3Ddisp=
layad&amp;utm_term=3D26&amp;utm_campaign=3D17&amp;g=3D3JY"><img src=3D"http=
s://data.wyzant.com/content/images/displayads/Algebra-468x60_new.jpg" alt=
=3D"Algebra Tutors" style=3D"display:block; margin:auto;"></a>
                  </div><!-- /WyzAnt text-link ad for non-mobile -->
                <hr>
                </div><!-- /hiding ads on printed pages -->
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <h4 class=3D"text question">Round <span class=3D"math">=
=CF=80</span> to four places.</h4>
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <div class=3D"indent_prob">
                  <p class=3D"text">First, I go back to the original number=
 (not the one I just rounded in the previous example). I count off four pla=
ces, and look at the number in the fifth place:</p>
                  <div class=3D"indent_prob">
                    <p class=3D"math">3.1415 | 9265...</p>
                  </div>
                  <p class=3D"text">The number in the fifth place is a <spa=
n class=3D"math">9</span>, which is greater than <span class=3D"math">5</sp=
an>, so I'll round up in the fourth place, truncating the expansion at four=
 decimal places. That is, the <span class=3D"math">5</span> becomes a <span=
 class=3D"math">6</span>, the <span class=3D"math">9265...</span> part disa=
ppears, and <span class=3D"math">=CF=80</span>, rounded to four decimal pla=
ces, is:</p>
                  <div class=3D"indent_prob">
                    <p class=3D"math answer">3.1416</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div style=3D"border-style:solid; border-radius:15px; borde=
r-width:1px; border-color:purple; padding:10px; margin:20px 0;">
                  <p class=3D"text">When rounding, you always start with th=
e original value, count out to the specified "place", and round. You <em>ne=
ver</em> round from the right, moving step-by-step to the left, until you r=
each the specified "place"!</p>
                  <p class=3D"text">For instance, if you were told to round=
 <span class=3D"math">5.7445</span> to two decimal places, it would be wron=
g to say "well, <span class=3D"math">5.7445</span> rounds to <span class=3D=
"math">5.745</span>, which rounds to <span class=3D"math">5.75</span>." Thi=
s is wrong!</p>
                  <p class=3D"text">Instead, use the original number, mark =
off the "place" in question =E2=80=94 <span class=3D"math">5.74 | 45</span>=
 =E2=80=94 and round from there to get <span class=3D"math">5.74</span>.</p=
>
                </div>
                <hr>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <h4 class=3D"text question">Round <span class=3D"math">=
=CF=80</span> to three places.</h4>
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <div class=3D"indent_prob">
                  <p class=3D"text">First, I ignore my result from the prev=
ious exercise and instead go back to the original number. I count off three=
 decimal places, and look at the digit in the fourth place:</p>
                  <div class=3D"indent_prob">
                    <p class=3D"math">3.141 | 59265...</p>
                  </div>
                  <p class=3D"text">The number in the fourth place is a <sp=
an class=3D"math">5</span>, which is the cut-off for rounding: if the numbe=
r in the next place (after the one you're rounding to) is <span class=3D"ma=
th">5</span> or greater, you round up. In this case, the <span class=3D"mat=
h">1</span> becomes a <span class=3D"math">2</span>, the <span class=3D"mat=
h">59265...</span> part disappears, and <span class=3D"math">=CF=80</span>,=
 rounded to three decimal places, is:</p>
                  <div class=3D"indent_prob">
                    <p class=3D"math answer">3.142</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <hr>
                <div class=3D"hide-print" style=3D"min-height:331px;"><!-- =
hiding ad on printed pages -->
                <p class=3D"in-lesson-resp-ad-header">Content Continues Bel=
ow</p>
                  <div class=3D"in-lesson-resp-ad align-center" style=3D"mi=
n-height:280px;">
                    <!-- Google "true" responsive ad -->
                   =20
                    <!-- in-lesson box (text&graphic) responsive -->
                    <ins class=3D"adsbygoogle" style=3D"display: block; hei=
ght: 280px;" data-ad-client=3D"ca-pub-0863636157410944" data-ad-slot=3D"481=
4341407" data-ad-format=3D"auto" data-full-width-responsive=3D"true" data-a=
dsbygoogle-status=3D"done"><div id=3D"aswift_1_host" style=3D"border: none;=
 height: 280px; width: 720px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; position: relative=
; visibility: visible; background-color: transparent; display: inline-block=
;"></div></ins>
                   =20
                    <!-- /Google "true" -->
                  </div>
                  <hr>
                </div><!-- /hiding ad on printed pages -->
                <p class=3D"text">Rounding works the same way when they tel=
l you to round to a certain named "place", such as "the hundredths place". =
The only difference is that you have to be a bit more careful in counting o=
ff the places you need. Just remember that the decimal places count off to =
the right in the same order as the counting numbers count off to the left. =
That is, for regular numbers, you have the place values:</p>
                <div class=3D"indent_prob">
                  <p class=3D"text">...(ten-thousands) (thousands) (hundred=
s) (tens) (ones) (decimal point)</p>
                </div>
                <p class=3D"text">For decimal places, you don't have a "one=
ths", but you do have the other fractions:</p>
                <div class=3D"indent_prob">
                  <p class=3D"text">(decimal point) (tenths) (hundredths) (=
thousandths) (ten-thousandths)...</p>
                </div>
                <p class=3D"text">For instance:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <h4 class=3D"text question">Round <span class=3D"math">=
=CF=80</span> to the nearest thousandth.</h4>
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <div class=3D"indent_prob">
                  <p class=3D"text">"The nearest thousandth" means that I n=
eed to count off three decimal places (tenths, hundredths, thousandths), an=
d then round:</p>
                  <div class=3D"indent_prob">
                    <p class=3D"math">3.141 | 59265...</p>
                  </div>
                  <p class=3D"text">Then <span class=3D"math">=CF=80</span>=
, rounded to the nearest thousandth, is:</p>
                  <div class=3D"indent_prob">
                    <p class=3D"answer math">3.142</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <hr>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <h4 class=3D"text question">Round <span class=3D"math">=
2.796</span> to the hundredths place.</h4>
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <div class=3D"indent_prob">
                  <p class=3D"text">The hundredths place is two decimal pla=
ces (just like "hundred" has two zeroes), so I'll count off two decimal pla=
ces, and round according to the third decimal place:</p>
                  <div class=3D"indent_prob">
                    <p class=3D"math">2.79 | 6</p>
                  </div>
                  <p class=3D"text">Since the third decimal place contains =
a <span class=3D"math">6</span>, which is greater than <span class=3D"math"=
>5</span>, I have to round up. But rounding up a <span class=3D"math">9</sp=
an> gives a <span class=3D"math">10</span>. In this case, I round the <span=
 class=3D"math">79</span> up to an <span class=3D"math">80</span>:</p>
                  <div class=3D"indent_prob">
                    <p class=3D"math answer">2.80</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <!-- WyzAnt mobile-only ad -->
                <div class=3D"alignright display-mobile hide-print" style=
=3D"width:180px; float:right; margin-left:10px; margin-top:20px;">
                  <p class=3D"in-lesson-resp-ad-header nomargin" align=3D"c=
enter">Affiliate</p>
                  <div id=3D"WyzAnt_Widget" class=3D"alignright" style=3D"m=
ax-width:160px;">
                    <div class=3D"wyzant wyzant-widget" data-widget-type=3D=
"side-search" data-api-key=3D"db8aced3-1979-4f99-bec1-650e0dfcb678" data-su=
bject=3D"algebra" data-size=3D"5" data-channel-id=3D"17"><div class=3D"side=
-widget side-widget-search"><div class=3D"logo"><img src=3D"https://partner=
-tools.wyzantcdn.com/sprocket/src/images/wyzant-logo.png"></div><p>Affordab=
le tutors for hire</p><form class=3D"form"><input type=3D"text" name=3D"sub=
ject" class=3D"form-control" placeholder=3D"Enter Subject" value=3D"algebra=
"><button type=3D"submit" class=3D"btn btn-block btn-primary"><i class=3D"w=
yzant-icon wyzant-icon-search"></i>Find tutors</button></form></div></div>
                  </div>
                </div><!-- /WyzAnt mobile-only ad -->
                <p class=3D"text">You might be tempted to write this as "<s=
pan class=3D"math">2.8</span>", but, since you rounded to the hundredths pl=
ace (to two decimal places), you should write both decimal places.</p>
                <p class=3D"text">Otherwise, it looks like you rounded to o=
ne decimal place, or to the tenths place, and your answer could be counted =
off as being incorrect.</p>
                               =20
                <div class=3D"hide-screen">
                	<hr>
                	<p id=3D"printout_URL">URL: https://www.purplemath.com/mod=
ules/rounding.htm</p>
                </div> =20
               =20
                <div class=3D"w3-container hide-print" style=3D"padding:20p=
